{{Infobox philosopher | name = Euthymius the Athonite | region = Byzantine Empire, Georgia | era = Middle Ages | image = St Euthymius of Athos (Akhtala fresco).JPG | caption = A 13th-century fresco of Euthymius from the [[Akhtala monastery]] | birth_date = {{circa}} 955 | death_date = c. 1024 | school_tradition= Eastern Theology | main_interests = [[Theology]], [[Art]], [[Literature]], [[Canon Law]] | influenced = | notable_ideas = ''[[sibrdzne balavarisa]]'' }}
'''Euthymius the Athonite''' ({{lang-ka|ექვთიმე ათონელი}} ''Ekvtime Atoneli''; {{circa}} 955–1024) was a renowned [[Georgians|Georgian]] [[Philosophy|philosopher]] and scholar. His feast day in the Orthodox Church is [[May 13 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)|May 13]].<ref>{{gr icon}} ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/3152/sxsaintinfo.aspx Ὁ Ὅσιος Εὐθύμιος ὁ Ἀθωνίτης κτήτορας τῆς Ι.Μ. Ἰβήρων].'' 13 Μαΐου. ΜΕΓΑΣ ΣΥΝΑΞΑΡΙΣΤΗΣ.</ref>
Euthymius was a Georgian, the ethnonym used by the Byzantines being ''Abasgians''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Elguja Xintʻibiże|title=Designations of the Georgians and their etymology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nHBpAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Tʻbilisis Universitetis Gamomcʻemloba|isbn=978-5-511-00775-5|page=73}}</ref> The son of [[Ioane Varaz-vache Chordvaneli]] and nephew of the great [[Tornike Eristavi]], Euthymius was taken as a political hostage to [[Constantinople]] but was later released and became a monk joining the [[Great Lavra]] of Athanasios on [[Mount Athos]]. He subsequently became the leader of the Georgian [[Iviron monastery]], which had been founded by his father,<ref name="Salia1983">{{cite book|author=Kalistrat Salia|title=History of the Georgian nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xjAhAQAAMAAJ|year=1983|publisher=N. Salia|page=82}}</ref> and emerged as one of the finest [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Christian]] [[theologians]] and scholars of his age. Fluent in [[Georgian language|Georgian]], [[Greek language|Greek]] and other languages, he translated many religious treatises and philosophical works. Among his major works was the translation of ''sibrdzne balavarisa'' (Wisdom of Balahvari), a Christianized version of episodes from the life of [[Gautama Buddha]] that became very popular in [[Medieval Europe]] as the story of [[Barlaam and Josaphat]]. Of equal importance was Euthymius’ work to prepare Georgian translations of various Greek philosophical, ecclesiastical and legal discourses.
