{{Infobox royalty | name =Grand Prince Yang Nyeong | title =Grand Prince of Joseon | image = | caption = | reign =1404 - 1418 | coronation =1404 | predecessor =[[Taejong of Joseon|Yi Bang-won]] | successor =Grand Prince Hyo Ryeong | consort = | issue = | royal house =[[House of Yi]] | royal anthem = | father =[[Taejong of Joseon]] | mother =[[Queen Wonkyeong]] | birth_date =1394 | birth_place =[[Seoul]] | death_date =1462 (aged 68) | death_place =Unknown | place of burial =[[Temple of Ji-duk]] | | module = {{Infobox Korean name |title=Korean name |hangul={{linktext|양|녕|대|군}} |hanja={{linktext|讓|寧|大|君|}} |rr=Yang Nyeong Daegun |mr=Yang Nyŏng Taekun |hangulborn={{linktext|이|제}} |hanjaborn={{linktext|李|褆|}} |rrborn=Yi Je |mrborn=Yi Che |hangulja={{linktext|후|백}} |hanjaja={{linktext|厚|伯|}} |rrja=Hubaek |mrja=Hupaek |hangulho={{linktext|강|정}} |hanjaho={{linktext|剛|靖|}} |rrho=Gangjeong |mrho=Kangjŏng | child = yes}} }}
'''Grand Prince Yangnyeong''' ([[Hangul]]: 양녕대군, [[Hanja]]: 讓寧大君, 1394–1462) was a [[Joseon dynasty]] politician and prince. The Grand Prince, first-born son of [[King Taejong]] of the [[Joseon dynasty]] and his consort [[Queen Wongyeong]], elder brother of [[Sejong the Great]], and ancestor of [[Syngman Rhee]], Korean independence activist and first [[Presidents of South Korea|President of South Korea]].
==Biography== He was born as '''Yi Je''' (李褆 in [[Hanja]], 이제 in [[Hangul]]) in 1394. Originally his father appointed him as the Crown Prince but he eventually executed the Queen Wongyeong's brothers and in the 18th year of his reign replaced prince Yangnyeong with his third son [[Sejong the Great|prince Chungnyeong]] as his successor <ref> https://books.google.ru/books?id=p3yW5MdzKnUC&pg=PA49&dq=Yangnyeong&hl=ru&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIovjtvPLeAhWSlIsKHeNECdAQ6AEITTAF#v=onepage&q=Yangnyeong&f=false </ref>. Known for his [[literature]] and [[calligraphy]] skills, the former Crown Prince viewed himself as lacking in the requisite skills for kingship and believed that [[Sejong the Great|Sejong]] was destined to become king. Considering it his duty to make Sejong king, he purposely acted extremely rude in the court, lost his position as a prince, married a peasant and was eventually officially banished from [[Seoul]] in June 1418. Grand Prince Hyoryeong, Yangnyeong's second brother, had similar feelings about Sejong being king, and so became a monk in a [[Buddhist]] temple. Possibly King Tajong's willingness to execute troublesome family members helped encourage his first two sons to step aside and allow King Taejong's third and favorite son to become King Sejong. This plot ultimately brought [[Sejong the Great|Sejong]] to the throne. Later, Yangnyeong became a wandering traveler and lived in the mountains.<ref>[http://100.naver.com/ Naver Encyclopedia], "[http://100.naver.com/100.nhn?docid=109130 양녕대군 [讓寧大君, 1394~1462<nowiki>]</nowiki>]", [[Naver]]"</ref>
After [[Sejong the Great|Sejong]] had taken the throne, the relationship between the brothers was strong, and Sejong often invited Yangnyeong to the palace.
Yangnyeong lived as a wanderer and died in 1462, almost living for 68 years.<ref>[http://100.naver.com/ Naver Encyclopedia], "[http://100.naver.com/100.nhn?docid=109130 양녕대군 [讓寧大君, 1394~1462<nowiki>]</nowiki>]", [[Naver]]"</ref>
